
	xvargs: approach to stdarg library from libc for x86_64
API
	* XVARG_SAFE: this macro is used in case the api-user wants a safe way to
	use xvargs. It makes xvargs to check a provided limit (via xvargs_init) and
	if such limit is exceeded, a default value (also provided via xvargs_init)
	is returned instead

	* xvargs_init: this function sets up the library, the main argument is the
	value of the `rbp` register of the caller's function (movq %rbp, %rdi), so
	xvargs_next knows from where to start reading. If XVARG_SAFE is present,
	then the function takes two more arguments
	- rsi: a limit for the number of arguments expected
	- rdx: a default value in case rsi's value is exceeded

	* xvargs_next: gives the next argument found. If XVARG_SAFE is present and
	the limit provided is exceeded, the function returns the default value

	* xvargs_fini: cleans the library information to make it ready for other functions.
	This library cannot be called more than once at the same time since there's only
	one set of variables to handle the metada
USAGE
	[       ]  | rbp				 0(offset from rbp)
	[       ]  | return address      8(offset from rbp)
	[ stack ]  | arg1				16(offset from rbp) ._xvargs_stack_offset = 0
	[       ]  | arg2                       .           ._xvargs_stack_offset = 1
	[       ]  | arg3                       .           ._xvargs_stack_offset = 2
	[       ]  v                            .

	Since the arguments are pushed into the stack, the arguments need to be pushed in
	the reversed order they're intended to be used. For example in C you would do
	something like

	function(1, 2, 3) using the library, you would need to make function(3, 2, 1)

